                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 738.3915/86.</note>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to Haiti</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-11-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 974.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Upon the receipt of the Department’s November 22,
                    2 p.m., I called upon Secretary Legér and tried to urge a conciliatory attitude
                    pending the settlement of the boundary dispute, but he absolutely refused to
                    consent to what he styles an invasion. He says that if the Dominicans do not
                    withdraw the Haitian Government will exert every possible means to force them to
                    do so. He insists that the status quo line be respected pending negotiations for
                    the permanent settlement of the question.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. W. Furniss.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
